{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":1078,"record_hash":"sha256:eb6630830390e5ee36814638ccbfe6a29b88714d7024e068f6b5f1e401f0e9c8","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:21:25.766Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 78b618\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1045\nOutput:\n\nCreate a session turn only when capture writes at least one new transcript\nrecord. An environment-only observation should not create a turn. Otherwise the\nmodel drifts from agent-session capture into repository telemetry.\n\nThe first hook run for a session may capture more than one actual conversation\nturn if it imports an existing transcript backlog. Later stop-hook runs should\nusually map more closely to one user/agent interaction. That distinction should\nstay visible in the model: a turn is a capture observation, not necessarily a\nprovider-native turn.\n\nFor first-time backfill, create one capture turn containing all newly written\nrecords and one environment snapshot from capture time. Provider-native turn\nidentifiers, when available, can be preserved as optional record-level grouping\nmetadata, but they should not become real session turns during backfill because\nhistorical repository environment snapshots cannot be reconstructed.\n\nStore a compact `capture_kind` on the turn:\n\n- `backfill`: the capture imported an existing transcript backlog\n- `incremental`: the capture observed new records from an ongoing session\n\nBackfill turns are valid transcript history, but their environment snapshot is\nweaker association evidence because it only describes capture time, not the time\neach historical provider turn happened.\n\n## Turn Data\n\nA turn needs an ID. The exact key shape is open, but the ID should be stable\nenough for idempotent repeated capture. Given a turn, it should be possible to\nfind the transcript records that were newly observed in that turn.\n\nTurn identity should be derived from capture content, not from time or provider\nturn ids. Use a 128-bit truncated SHA-256 value: take the first 16 bytes of the\ndigest and render them as 32 lowercase hex characters.\n\n```text\nturn-key = sha256-trunc128(session_key + NUL + source_key + NUL + ordered_new_record_hashes)\n```\n\nThat makes the newly accepted transcript \n[TRUNCATED]\ne same turn key.\n\nProvider-native turn identifiers should not define the durable `turn-key`.\nProviders may omit them, define turns differently, expose private/raw ids, or\ninclude many provider turns inside one first-time backfill capture. If present,\nthey can be stored as optional record-level grouping metadata, preferably as a\nsafe provider turn key rather than a raw provider id.\n\nMinimum useful fields:\n\n- turn id\n- session key\n- source key\n- capture kind\n- capture timestamp\n- transcript record membership, probably by record hash and/or source record\n  index\n- optional provider turn key on transcript records, for grouping/display only\n- previous turn reference, when there is a previous capture turn in the same\n  session\n- environment snapshot\n\nThe record membership matters because `but-agentlog` already deduplicates\nrecords. Without turn membership, repeated hook capture preserves the transcript\nbut erases the boundaries between capture invocations.\n\nThe model should distinguish:\n\n- **capture turn:** a stop-hook capture observation with new transcript records\n  and a repository environment snapshot\n- **provider turn:** a provider-native conversation grouping, such as a user\n  prompt and the resulting assistant/tool activity\n\nCapture turns are the durable agentlog concept. Provider turns are useful for UI\ngrouping when available, but they are not portable enough to define the storage\nmodel across agents.\n\nStore `previous_turn_key` as a session-wide previous capture turn pointer when\nit is available. It is not part of turn identity. It exists to make interval\nevidence cheap to evaluate, for example \"worktree files seen in the previous\nturn later appeared in commits visible in this turn.\" The first turn omits the\nfield.\n\nImplementation should write transcript records, record hashes, the turn object,\nthe turn list entry, and derived index entries as one logical GitMeta update.\nIf transcript record writes can succeed while the turn write fails, a later\nretry may see zero new records and skip the missing turn.\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:21:25.766Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}